If the New Deal &quot;solved chronic demand problems&quot;, why for the eleven-year period of 1930 to 1940 did net private investment total minus $3.1 billion. Only in 1941 did net private investment ($9.7 billion) exceed the 1929 amount.  Or why did unemployment stay above 10% from 1931-1940?  Perhaps the New Deal did not help as much as one might think, or perhaps the New Deal made things worse, although clearly something caused an economic improvement in 1933.  Milton Friedman and I believe it was the devaluation of the dollar, and this may also explain why the UK, who went off the gold standard earlier, ended up fairing better through the Great Depression. <a class="read-more" href="#">Read more</a>
